 web |url=http://nyslovesfilm.tumblr.com/post/141970211803/march-is-busy-with-new-york-produced-films-and |title=March Is Busy With New York-Produced Films and Premieres |work=tumblr.com |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Orange County, New York]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orangecountynyfilm.org/filmed-in-orange-county/ |title=Filmed in Orange County NY \u2013 Orange County Film Office \u2013 Orange County, NY \u2013 OCNY FILM Office |work=orangecountynyfilm.org |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thephoto-news.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20160310/NEWS01/160319993/Monroe--Woodbury-High-School-to-be-the-set-of-new-Netflix-series |title=Monroe- Woodbury High School to be the set of new Netflix series \u2013 Monroe Woodbury NY \u2013 Local News |work=thephoto-news.com |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Groton, Connecticut]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theday.com/article/20160510/NWS01/160519954 |first=Kristina |last=Dorsey |title=Netflix series wraps a two-day shoot in Groton |work=The Day |date=May 10, 2016 |accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lol Crawley]]\n* Steven Meizler\n* Magnus Nordenhof J\u00f8nck\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jonathan Alberts\n* Geraud Brisson\n* Matthew Hannam\n* [[Lisa Lassek]]\n* [[Andrew Weisblum]]\n* Alex O'Flinn\n* Neil Meiklejohn\n* Luke Ciarrocchi\n* Blake Holland\n* Saela Davis\n}}\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 31\u201371 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Plan B Entertainment]]\n* [[Anonymous Content]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Netflix|Netflix Studios]]<ref>https://trademarks.justia.com/867/68/the-86768143.html</ref>\n| network                  = Netflix\n| picture_format           = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital Plus]] 5.1 with [[Descriptive Video Service]] track\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2019|3|22}}\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/theoa\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       =\n}}\n'''''The OA''''' is an American [[Mystery film|mystery]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[web television]] series with [[science fiction]], [[Supernatural fiction|supernatural]], and [[fantasy (genre)|fantasy]] elements.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/doyle-netflixs-mysterious-the-oa-is-mind-bending-astounding-drama/article33344922/ |title=John Doyle: Netflix's mysterious ''The OA'' is mind-bending drama |work=theglobeandmail.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/could-oa-new-stranger-things-know-far-netflixs-mysterious-new/ |title=Could ''The OA'' be the new ''Stranger Things''? All we know so far about Netflix's mysterious new show |work=telegraph.co.uk |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> ''The OA'' debuted on [[Netflix]] on December 16, 2016.<ref name=\"DL trailer\">{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/the-oa-trailer-premiere-date-netflix-brit-marling-1201868844/ |title=''The OA'' Trailer: Netflix Releases First Look & Sets Premiere Date For Drama |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 12, 2016 |accessdate=December 12, 2016 |first=Erik |last=Pedersen}}</ref><ref name=\"digital spy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/news/a633457/netflix-orders-new-original-series-the-oa-starring-brit-marling.html#~p65N7NAAIF4OQo |title=Netflix orders new original series ''The OA'' starring Brit Marling |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=March 5, 2015 |accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> Created and executive produced by [[Brit Marling]] and [[Zal Batmanglij]], the series is their third collaboration.<ref name=\"DL trailer\" /><ref name=\"digital spy\" /> The series consists of two seasons of eight episodes each, nearly all directed by Batmanglij, and is produced by [[Plan B Entertainment]] and [[Anonymous Content]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/netflix-the-oa-brit-marling-zal-batmanglij-plan-b-anonymous-content-1201386609/ |title=Netflix Greenlights ''The OA'' Reuniting Brit Marling And Zal Batmanglij |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 5, 2015 |accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> In the series, Marling stars as a young woman named Prairie Johnson who resurfaces after having been missing for seven years. Prairie now calls herself \"The OA\" and can see, despite having been blind before her disappearance.\n\nOn February 8, 2017, Netflix renewed the series for a second season, dubbed \"Part II\", that was released on March 22, 2019. Although the OA was planned by its creators to be a five-part story told in five seasons,<ref name=\"Netflix VP Confirms 5 Season Plan\">{{cite news |last1=Travers |first1=Ben |title='The OA\u2019 Season 2: Netflix VP Says \u2018Fans Will Be Very Happy\u2019 with New Episodes and Confirms Five-Season Plan |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/the-oa-season-2-netflix-fantastic-five-season-plan-1201989088/ |accessdate=August 15, 2019 |work=IndieWire |date=June 29, 2018}}</ref> on August 5, 2019, Netflix canceled the series after two seasons, leaving the show with a [[cliffhanger]] ending.<ref name=\"THRCanceled\">{{cite news |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |title=''The OA'' Canceled After Two Seasons at Netflix |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/oa-canceled-two-seasons-at-netflix-1229215 |accessdate=August 5, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> ''The OA'' received generally favorable critical reception, averaging 77% on Part I and 92% on Part II on Rotten Tomatoes. The series' directing, visuals and acting were often singled out, as was its social impact.<ref name=\"The OA may have been Canceled, but Few Shows Can Claim the Same Social Impact\">{{cite news |last1=Osenlund |first1=R. Kurt R. |title=\u2018The OA\u2019 May Have Been Canceled, but Few Shows Can Claim the Same Social Impact |url=https://observer.com/2019/08/the-oa-netflix-canceled-brit-marling-message-petition-movement/ |accessdate=August 15, 2019 |work=Observer |date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n===Part I===\nThe series centers around Prairie Johnson, an adopted young woman who resurfaces after having been missing for seven years. Upon her return, Prairie calls herself \"The OA\" (for \"Original Angel\"), exhibits scars on her back, and can see, despite having been blind when she disappeared. The OA refuses to tell the [[FBI]] and her adoptive parents where she has been and how her eyesight was restored, and instead quickly assembles a team of five locals (four high school students and a teacher) to whom she reveals that information, also explaining her life story. Finally, she asks for their help to save the other missing people whom she claims she can rescue by opening a portal to [[Parallel universes in fiction|another dimension]].<ref name=\"Gilbert2019\">{{cite news |last1=Gilbert |first1=Sophie |title=The Radical Sincerity of The OA |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/03/the-return-of-the-oa-tvs-strangest-most-sincere-show/585208/ |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Part II===\nThe second season follows the OA as she traverses to another dimension and ends up in [[San Francisco]] to continue her search for her former captor Hap and her fellow captives. Prairie crosses paths with [[Private investigator|private eye]] Karim Washington and assists in his investigation of the surreal disappearance of a missing girl that involves an abandoned house with a supernatural history and an online puzzle game. Meanwhile, in the original dimension, a series of unfortunate events propels the OA's five companions to embark on a road trip across America to assist the OA on her journey.\n\n==Cast==\nThe following actors appear in the series:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/brit-marling-netflix-the-oa-mystery-trailer-video/ |title=Brit Marling's Netflix Series ''The OA'' Promises Mystery in First Trailer (Video) |work=The Wrap |date=December 12, 2016 |accessdate=December 12, 2016 |first=Linda |last=Ge}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/the-oa-brandon-perea-will-brill-cast-netflix-drama-series-1201708672/ |title=''The OA'': Brandon Perea & Will Brill Join Netflix Drama Series |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 24, 2016 |accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Main ===\n* [[Brit Marling]] as Prairie Johnson / the OA / Nina Azarova / \"Brit\"\n* [[Emory Cohen]] as Homer Roberts<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/01/oa-emory-cohen-defends-the-movements.html |title=The OA's Emory Cohen Defends the Movements |date=January 13, 2017 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]] as Abel Johnson, Prairie's adoptive father (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Phyllis Smith]] as Betty \"BBA\" Broderick-Allen<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/the-oa-netflix-phyllis-smith.html |title=The OA's Phyllis Smith Talks Angels, Turtles, and Dance Moves |date=December 23, 2016 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Alice Krige]] as Nancy Johnson, Prairie's adoptive mother (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Patrick Gibson (actor)|Patrick Gibson]] as Steve Winchell / \"Patrick Gibson\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/oa-breakout-star-patrick-gibson-mysteries-new-netflix-hit-and-possible-season-536880 |title=Inside Netflix's new cult hit ''The OA'' with breakout star Patrick Gibson |work=newsweek.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Brendan Meyer]] as Jesse \n* [[Brandon Perea]] as Alfonso \"French\" Sosa\n* [[Ian Alexander (actor)|Ian Alexander]] as Buck/Michelle Vu<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/the-oa-netflix-ian-alexander-buck.html |title=The OA's Ian Alexander on His Big Acting Debut and Trans Representation |date=December 22, 2016 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jason Isaacs]] as Hunter Aloysius \"Hap\" Percy / Dr. Percy / \"Jason Isaacs\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/news/a51705/jason-isaacs-the-oa-interview/ |title=''The OA''{{'}}s Jason Isaacs Is Just as Bewildered by the Netflix Series as You Are|date=December 21, 2016|work=esquire.com|accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Kingsley Ben-Adir]] as Karim Washington (season 2)\n* [[Will Brill]] as Scott Brown (season 2, recurring season 1)\n* [[Sharon Van Etten]] as Rachel DeGrasso (season 2, recurring season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/01/sharon-van-etten-the-oa-twin-peaks.html |title=Sharon Van Etten on The OA, Twin Peaks, and Her 'Surreal' Acting Debut |date=January 10, 2017 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Paz Vega]] as Renata Duarte (season 2, recurring season 1)\n* [[Chloe Levine]] as Angie (season 2, recurring season 1)\n\n=== Guest ===\n* [[Hiam Abbass]] as [[Khatun]] (season 1)\n* [[Evgeniya Brik#Family|Zoey Todorovsky]] as Nina Azarova, a young Prairie Johnson\n* Marcus Choi as Mr. Vu\n* Robert Eli as Ellis Gilchrist, a high school principal (season 1)\n* [[Nikolai Nikolaeff]] as Roman Azarov, Nina's father \n* [[Sean Grandillo]] as Miles Brekov (season 1)\n* Zachary Gemino as Carlos Sosa, Alfonso's brother \n* [[Riz Ahmed]] as Elias Rahim, an FBI trauma counselor\n* [[Robert Morgan (actor)|Robert Morgan]] as Stan Markham, a sheriff (season 1)\n* [[Michael Cumpsty]] as Leon Citro (season 1)\n* [[Bria Vinaite]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/kidding-cast-bernard-white-bria-vinaite-the-oa-1202395573/ |title=''Kidding'' Casts Bernard White; Bria Vinaite Joins ''The OA'' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=May 22, 2018 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> as Darmi (season 2)\n* [[Zendaya]] as Fola Uzaki (season 2)\n* [[Zo\u00eb Chao]] as Mo (season 2)\n* [[Ir\u00e8ne Jacob]] as \u00c9lodie (season 2)\n* [[Eijiro Ozaki]] as [[Azrael]] / Old Night, a giant octopus (voice) (season 2)\n* [[Vincent Kartheiser]] as Pierre Ruskin (season 2)\n* [[Liz Carr]] as Marlow Rhodes (season 2)\n* [[Melora Walters]] as Melody, who accompanies OA to the clinic in the episode \"Angel of Death\"\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| allreleased = y\n| released    = y\n\n| color1     = #1D1023\n| link1      = #Part I (2016)\n| episodes1  = 8\n| start1     = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n\n| color2     = #16365C\n| link2      = #Part II (2019)\n| episodes2  = 8\n| start2     = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n}}\n\n===Part I (2016)===\n{{Episode table |background=#1D1023 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=28 |director=13 |writer=30 |airdate=19 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Chapter 1: Homecoming\n| DirectedBy      = [[Zal Batmanglij]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Brit Marling]] & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = After disappearing seven years ago, Prairie Johnson returns to her parents, Nancy and Abel. Prairie disappeared blind, but now she can see, and insists that her name is \"The OA\". She does not reveal how she regained her eyesight, nor where she has been for the past seven years, although she makes vague allusions to being held hostage with others. OA tells Steve, a neighborhood bully, that she will save him from being sent to [[Boot camp (correctional)|boot camp]] in Asheville, if he presents her with four other strong people. That night, OA meets Steve in an abandoned house with three other boys from his school, \"French\", Buck, and Jesse, along with their teacher, Betty Broderick-Allen (\"BBA\"). She tells them that she was born in [[Russia]] as Nina Azarova, the daughter of a powerful [[Russian oligarch|oligarch]]. One day, following a premonition she had, the mafia knocked the bus of the oligarchs' children into a river. Nina had a [[near-death experience]] (NDE), where a woman named Khatun gave her the choice of returning to life. Nina came back blind after Khatun told her she would take her sight to protect her from the horrible things lying ahead.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Chapter 2: New Colossus\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = [[Melanie Marnich]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Continuing her story, OA says that her father sent her to a [[boarding school]] for blind children in America to protect her. However, her father died, and she was sent to live with her aunt who ran an illegal adoption service. Nancy and Abel adopted her and named her Prairie. For the next several years, Prairie had dreams and premonitions, for which her parents [[Antipsychotic|medicated]] her. In them, her father waited for her by the [[Statue of Liberty]]. She ran away on her 21st birthday to see him, but he did not appear. Instead, she met a scientist named \"Hap\". She ends her story for the night, and the boys begin to investigate whether she is telling the truth. French considers not going again when he gets a scholarship and wishes to focus on that, but Buck convinces him to come. The next night, she tells them that Hap was studying people that had NDEs, like she did. Prairie agreed to let Hap study her and flew on his private plane to his house, where he trapped her in a glass cage in his basement, with the other test subjects he had tricked over the years.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Chapter 3: Champion\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Dominic Orlando\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = In the present, a journalist approaches Prairie's mother, asking if she can write a book about their story. In the flashback, Prairie gets to know Homer, Scott and Rachel, the other three captives. Prairie makes Hap a sandwich, and he takes her on as a cook. He regularly pumps gas to their cages as part of an experiment, but the four cannot figure what that is, as the gas makes them pass out. BBA defends Steve from being sent to Asheville, convincing his parents to put him in [[special education]] instead. Prairie makes soup for Hap, who experiences anaphylactic shock when he eats it. He asks her to get an [[EpiPen]] from the bathroom, but there she discovers the dead body of a girl \"August\". The captives try to send a letter for help, but lose it. Prairie asks Hap about August, but becomes angry and pushes him down the stairs, and flees. She makes it as far as a cliff, but gets hit in the head by a rifle butt.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Chapter 4: Away\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Ruby Rae Spiegel\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Prairie meets Khatun in NDE. She is offered the choice of reuniting with her father but she chooses to return to help the others. Khatun, who shows she has a bird wing, offers Prairie to swallow a bird which will show her a way of traveling unknown to humans. She tells Prairie that five of them must work together to avert a great evil and that Prairie is \"the original\". Hap returns Prairie to her cage and she tells the others that she can see, they are all [[angels]], and their way out is by figuring Hap's experiment. In the present, BBA learns her brother Theo left her $50,000 in his will. OA meets an FBI counselor, Elias, who suggests to her that she focus on healing herself. In her story, Prairie and Rachel decide to suck Hap's [[Hyoscine#Crime|scopolamine-like]] gas, so that Homer experiences the experiment awake. Hap is revealed to be drowning them in water and recording the soundscape of their NDEs. It takes Homer four years, but he experiences an NDE awake, in which he manages to swallow a sea anemone. Prairie contemplates the possibility that she has a truer self who answers to something sounding like \"Away\" or \"Oh-A\".\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Chapter 5: Paradise\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = OA (having abandoned the name Prairie) and Homer perform the two movements they got from their NDEs. Hap forces Homer to seduce an NDE survivor in [[Cuba]] named Renata, to kidnap her. Homer ends up sleeping with her, which destroys the morale of the team and hurts OA. With Renata now locked back at Hap's, it's Scott's turn for the experiment. Scott begs Hap to spare him as he is too sick to survive another NDE and reveals OA can see, and her ideas about angels and how to escape. Hap proceeds with the experiment and Scott dies. Hap takes his body back to his cage, telling OA it's her fault. OA and Homer do their movements for hours, while facing each other with Scott in the middle. Unexpectedly, Scott returns to life and tells them they were right; if at least five people perform the movements, a door to another dimension opens. He has been given the third of five. Hap runs downstairs in shock that Scott is alive. In present day, OA tells the others the reason she gathered them is to teach them the movements so that she may travel to another dimension and rescue the others.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Chapter 6: Forking Paths\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Melanie Marnich\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = In the following three years Renata gets the fourth movement, OA and Homer scar themselves with depictions of them, so that they don't forget them, and Hap is watching closely and learning their movements as well. Hap visits his former mentor, Leon, in a morgue, in which Leon also runs similar experiments. Leon tells Hap he is very close to proving the existence of [[afterlife]], but Hap tells him he actually believes there are multiple dimensions, and his subjects have the means to make traveling between them possible. He also thinks he knows where their NDEs take place, and he intends to go see it with his own eyes. Leon pulls a gun on Hap demanding he reveals his breakthroughs. They fight and Hap kills him. Hap leaves the hospital and informs the staff to call the police to rescue Leon's subjects. Later, he asks OA to leave with him, make money using the first two healing movements, and run experiments on their own, but she turns him down. He reveals to her he thinks her NDEs take her to the [[rings of Saturn]]. A sheriff pays Hap a visit and discovers the hostages. He aims his gun at Hap.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Chapter 7: Empire of Light\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = OA has a premonition of a big space with a metallic sound, but she cannot tell what it means. She discusses it with Elias, who suggest that her \"psychic\" capability might be the result of being able to notice even the smallest cues around her. He also tells her to just accept whatever happens. Steve is being sent to Asheville but BBA uses her inheritance check to bribe the drivers to let him go. OA has dinner with her parents, when Nancy gets upset that she knows nothing about what happened to her daughter. OA explains that she scarred herself with the notations of the movements that open another dimension and she knows all this because she is \"the Original Angel\", which causes Nancy to slap her. French suggests to OA that she forgive Nancy and Abel and consider them as her parents because they are one of the reasons she came back from her NDEs. Steve accuses OA of using him and the rest of the group just so she can return to Homer, then stabs her leg with a pencil. She embraces him and calms him down. He asks her how she survived all those years and she replies she did because she was not alone.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Chapter 8: Invisible Self\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Hap convinces the sheriff that OA and Homer can cure his dying wife. Once healed, the sheriff's wife reveals she is an NDE survivor and can give them the fifth movement. Upon doing so, Hap kills her and her husband. He releases OA on the side of the road, telling her he will jump dimensions with the others. French breaks into OA's house, discovers some books that relate to OA's story (e.g., [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]''), and shares the revelation with the others. Days later, a [[School shooting|shooter]] approaches the school cafeteria where the boys are eating lunch. The boys and BBA, fearing for the lives of all present, desperately decide to enact OA's five movements. Bewildered, the shooter is easily subdued, but a stray bullet hits OA through the cafeteria window where she had been watching from outside. As medics tend to her, OA tells the boys and BBA that she can now feel herself going to another dimension.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n}}\n\n===Part II (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#16365C |overall=5 |season=5 |title=28 |director=13 |writer=30 |airdate=19 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = Chapter 1: Angel of Death\n |DirectedBy = [[Zal Batmanglij]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Brit Marling]] & Zal Batmanglij\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = In San Francisco, private detective Karim Washington agrees to help an elderly Vietnamese woman find her missing granddaughter, Michelle. Karim discovers Michelle's former hideout in an abandoned house, where she won tens of thousands of dollars playing \"Q Symphony,\" an online puzzle game. Karim theorizes the game is a recruitment and [[crowdsourcing]] tool created by tech guru Pierre Ruskin. Karim infiltrates the Q Symphony headquarters and finds inmates having their dreams monitored. Meanwhile, an adult Nina Azarova collapses in San Francisco as Prairie is shot; Prairie awakens in Nina's body, in an alternate dimension where Joe Biden is [[President of the United States|President]] in 2016. Nina was never blind, her father lived into old age, and Pierre Ruskin is her boyfriend. She contacts Nancy, who doesn't know her, having gone through with her original intention to adopt a boy. Due to her erratic behavior, Prairie is put on [[involuntary commitment|psychiatric hold]], but accepts an offer to check into the secluded Treasure Island psychiatric hospital. Homer is a [[residency (medicine)|resident]] psychiatrist and does not recognize her. Rachel, Scott, and Renata are patients. The facility's director is Hap, who greets her as \"Prairie.\"\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Chapter 2: Treasure Island\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Damien Ober & Nicki Paluga\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Hap continues to tighten his grip on Prairie by placing her in isolation from the other captives. Prairie unsuccessfully tries to help Homer remember his life from the original dimension. Out of sympathy, Homer decides to allow Prairie to reconcile with Scott, Rachel, and Renata. Rachel, having no longer the ability to speak, then uses objects to tell Prairie that Hap is planning to make a map across the multiple dimensions for his benefits. Meanwhile, Karim meets Marlow Rhodes, a former doctor who worked for Ruskin, who says that the house is a benefactor of the dreams. Karim realizes that the house is put on a Russian trust owned by Nina, Ruskin's girlfriend, and he decides to go see Prairie/Nina at the clinic. Hap takes Rachel to assist in his experiment on the clinic. Rachel comes across a classified area in Hap's experiment where she sees something horrific. Rachel stabs Hap in the stomach and Hap breaks her neck, killing her. Rachel's subconscious then transfers from her body to the original dimension from the prior season, where she finds sanctuary in the vanity mirror of Buck's room.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = Chapter 3: Magic Mirror\n |DirectedBy = [[Andrew Haigh]]\n |WrittenBy = Nicki Paluga & Dominic Orlando\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Back in the original dimension, Prairie died after being shot at the school. Her companions struggle to cope with the loss: Buck and BBA are about to move away; Steve and his new girlfriend Angie debate about teaching the movements to others to continue Prairie's legacy; Jesse becomes depressed following his brush with death; French struggles with his faith to OA. Suddenly, Buck sees a vision of Rachel on his vanity mirror and contacts the group, but the vanity was sold behind their back to a faraway department center, forcing them to drive hundreds of miles to successfully get the mirror. They take sanctuary at a church, and French temporarily splits from the group and has a one-night-stand with a man who recommends a psychic in Nebraska for support. The group then treks there, but the vanity accidentally gets broken. At the psychic's house, she helps Rachel come into contact with the group through a television. The group deduces from Rachel's messages that Prairie successfully made it to another dimension, and that it is \"only safe for BBA to go\" there.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Chapter 4: SYZYGY\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = After Rachel's murder, Hap incinerates her corpse. Karim visits Prairie/Nina to find out about her involvement in CURI. Prairie pleads with Karim to help her get out of the clinic in exchange for her assisting Karim in his case. They come to an agreement and they break out of the clinic. Homer goes on an unsuccessful date and Hap meets an enigmatic woman named Elodie who claims that she too is an inter-dimensional traveler like Hap. Meanwhile, Prairie and Karim head inside Nina's apartment and find a closet full of cassette tapes and a note marked \"SYZYGY\", in reference to a bar in downtown San Francisco. Prairie heads to the bar as Nina, alongside Karim, who looks for more clues in the venue. Prairie is strapped to a chair on the stage where a telepathic octopus, Old Night, straps his tentacles onto Prairie and has her communicate messages via his telepathy. Old Night figures out Prairie's true self, the OA, and strangles her to death to help her find clues in her investigation. A shocked Karim cuts one of Old Night's tentacles off, killing him, and resuscitates Prairie. They flee down the bar's basement and go through a door similar to one shown in Q Symphony.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = Chapter 5: The Medium & the Engineer\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Damien Ober & [[Henry Bean]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Prairie and Karim go through a sewer that leads them to inside the house on Nob Hill. They then solve some of the house's puzzles together, until they somehow split from each other. Karim explores the labyrinthine sections of the house and finds an unconscious Fola. He breaks through one of the walls, and escorts Fola, managing to save her in the process. Prairie journeys deeper inside, where she comes across a flock of living, telepathic trees that tell her that Hap is planning to make a powerful discovery that would make her lose her faith. The trees warn Prairie to form a tribe and that Nina is the key to doing so. Meanwhile, Homer comes across incriminating files that implicate Hap's involvement in CURI as his recorded conversations with Ruskin recall the history of the house. He also uncovers Hap's lie about Rachel, as he finds out that Rachel wasn't sent to another clinic. Meanwhile, in Elodie's apartment, Hap tries to knock out Elodie to use for his experiments. However, she catches wind of his intentions and uses cubes of dancing robots that initiate the movements, sending her to another dimension and killing her. A shocked Hap leaves the premises.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Chapter 6: Mirror Mirror\n |DirectedBy = Andrew Haigh\n |WrittenBy = Dominic Orlando & Claire Kiechel\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = BBA and the boys continue their journey across America. Their car breaks down and they hitchhike to a restaurant, where Jesse theorizes that they should head to Treasure Island in San Francisco to look for Prairie. They realize through television that they're wanted fugitives, and that an Amber alert is put out on Buck, a minor. They flee to avoid attention and take a bus trip to the house of BBA's dying uncle Carl in California where they stay for a day. However, things take a tragic turn when Jesse fatally overdoses on Carl's medication and the group tries to save him to no avail. They leave, but Steve stays behind to hopefully revive Jesse a second time. Unsuccessful and exhausted, he suddenly shaves his head. Meanwhile, Buck, Angie, French and BBA mourn Jesse's loss at a motel room and discuss going to Treasure Island, until Prairie's psychologist, Elias, arrives at their room and suggests that they should continue on with their journey as he claims that Prairie is going to need their help on her journey as the OA. The group then decides to trek to Treasure Island.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = Chapter 7: Nina Azarova\n |DirectedBy = [[Anna Rose Holmer]]\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Henry Bean\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Homer briefly confronts Hap about Rachel's whereabouts but Hap lies, telling Homer that Rachel killed herself. Homer then tells Hap that Scott explained about his NDE, where he sees Hap and Prairie together in a vision of a different dimension. Hap then contacts Scott, offering him his and Renata's freedom if he helps navigate the house on Nob Hill; Scott accepts the offer. Scott goes inside the house, but he suddenly collapses and is collected by Hap to be experimented on. Meanwhile, Prairie and Karim reunite as they find video footage of Michelle in the house's attic. They then have a falling out after Karim is unfazed by Prairie's claims about the dimensions and of Buck/Michelle. Prairie then crosses paths with Elodie, who advises her to let Nina have control of her body as well. Prairie drowns herself in a bathtub and resurrects as Nina. She then heads to Treasure Island and asks to talk to Hap. Meanwhile, Karim confronts Ruskin, who brags about getting away with his wrongdoings with the house because he believes nobody will come after him. He reveals that Michelle is alive but in a coma and that the house started to dream about Karim, calling for him to come back.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Chapter 8: Overview\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Prairie helps Homer remember his memories and manages to convince Hap to show his research: mutated humans in a vegetated pool that serve as glimpses to other dimensions. They are revealed to be Scott and alternate versions of French, Jesse, and Steve. Prairie reverts back to herself and belittles Hap for his cruelty. Hap corners her into a spot surrounded by robots that initiate the movements to send them to another dimension. Hap fatally shoots Homer and Prairie tells a dying Homer to look for her in the next dimension. In the original dimension, Steve and the group reunite at Treasure Island, where BBA can sense OA's presence in danger and they initiate the movements to help her until Steve collapses. Karim makes it into the attic of the Nob Hill house, having solved the puzzle, and witnesses Prairie floating in the sky. She suddenly falls down, transitioning her to the third dimension with Hap. It is revealed that the next dimension is inside the soundstage of a television show, where an injured Prairie is referred to as \"Brit\" and Hap is her husband, \"Jason Isaacs\", who has a British accent. Karim notices a version of Buck in that universe and calls for him, as Buck is pulled inside the attic by Karim, waking up Michelle from her coma. Prairie and Hap get inside an ambulance but Steve, having successfully jumped dimensions, catches up, reuniting with Prairie and recognizing \"Jason Isaacs\" as Hap.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe series was conceived by Brit Marling and Zal Batmanglij and they began working on the concept in December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theplaylist.net/director-zal-batmanglij-talks-creating-oa-season-2-will-evolve-much-interview-20170113/ |title=Director Zal Batmanglij Talks Creating ''The OA'', How Season 2 Will Evolve, And Much More [Interview] |date=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvmag.lefigaro.fr/programme-tv/the-oa-la-serie-revolutionnaire-de-netflix-racontee-par-sa-creatrice_a3e4d57c-c784-11e6-adad-3999a46f423c/ |title=The OA, la s\u00e9rie \"r\u00e9volutionnaire\" de Netflix racont\u00e9e par.. |last=lefigaro.fr |date=December 21, 2016 |work=lefigaro.fr |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> They spent two years working on ''The OA'' on their own,<ref name=\"Plan B\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marieclaire.com/culture/interviews/a24243/brit-marling-the-oa-interview/ |title=Brit Marling Spills on Her Mysterious New Netflix Show ''The OA'' |date=December 16, 2016 |work=marieclaire.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> before pitching to studios.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-oa-co-creator-on-stranger-things-comparisons-keeping-the-show-under-wraps/ |title=''The OA'' Co-Creator on ''Stranger Things'' Comparisons |date=December 16, 2016 |work=thewrap.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> From the early stages of development onward, they were telling the story out loud and noting one another's reactions to the story to refine it accordingly.<ref name=\"pitch\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/brit-marling-the-oa-netflix.html |title=Brit Marling on The OA, Netflix's Surprise Show About Dying |date=December 19, 2016 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> They found it difficult to summarize the series in a written story, so they developed it aurally. When executives read the script of the first hour, they asked if the story \"really [went] somewhere\". Marling and Batmanglij then began to tell the story from beginning to end,<ref name=\"pitch\" /> playing all the characters and acting out the big moments through many hours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/the-frame/2016/12/16/53836/how-the-creators-of-the-oa-made-a-long-format-mind/ |title=How the creators of ''The OA'' made a 'long format mind-bender' |first=Southern California Public |last=Radio |date=December 16, 2016 |work=scpr.org |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> They worked with [[Brad Pitt]]'s [[Plan B Entertainment]], which connected with the story and shared notes before it went to networks and studios.<ref name=\"Plan B\" /> Following a multiple-network bidding war, the series was first announced on March 5, 2015, when Netflix ordered eight one-hour long episodes with Plan B and [[Anonymous Content]] also on board. The announcement revealed that Marling would star, Batmanglij would direct, and both would write and executive produce. Marling and Batmanglij held similar positions in their previous two collaborations, ''[[Sound of My Voice]]'' and ''[[The East (film)|The East]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/brit-marling-zal-batmanglij-drama-779380 |title=Brit Marling-Zal Batmanglij Drama Gets Netflix Series Order (Exclusive) |work=hollywoodreporter.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Rostam Batmanglij]], Zal's brother, worked as one of the composers on the series, and he also wrote its theme music.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/16/t-magazine/entertainment/the-oa-brit-marling-netflix.html |title=Character Building: Brit Marling |date=December 16, 2016 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> He previously composed for both ''Sound of My Voice'' and ''The East''. Choreographer [[Ryan Heffington]] created The Movements, which are inspired by [[interpretive dance]]. Heffington first professionally worked with them on ''The East'', and had been an acquaintance of both from earlier than that.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/the-oa-movements-ryan-heffington-choreography.html |title=''The OA''{{'}}s Choreographer on the Meaning of the 'Movements'|date=December 21, 2016|work=vulture.com|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe final chapter of Part I includes a dedication to Allison Wilke. Wilke, also known professionally as A.W. Gryphon, was a producer on the series who died of breast cancer three days after the series was finished and a month before its release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/what-oa-who-allison-wilke-9597164 |title=Answers to your The OA questions including season 2 and who is Allison Wilke |first=Jo-Anne |last=Rowney |date=10 January 2017 |work=mirror.co.uk |accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Cancellation and fan response==\nOn August 5, 2019, Netflix canceled the series after two seasons,<ref name=\"THRCanceled\" /> leaving the show with a [[cliffhanger]] ending. Marling wrote that she and Batmanglij were \"deeply sad\" that they would not be able to finish the show.<ref name=\"people\">{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/tv/the-oa-canceled-after-2-seasons/ |title=Celebrities and Fans 'Devastated' After Netflix Cancels The OA |last=Claudia |first=Harmata |website=PEOPLE.com |access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> Fans responded with a #SaveTheOA<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/5/20755034/the-oa-canceled-netflix-season-2 |title=Netflix cancels The OA after two seasons |last=Haasch |first=Palmer |date=2019-08-05 |website=Polygon |access-date=2019-08-07}}\"Fans begin rallying behind #SaveTheOA\"</ref> and #TheOAisReal campaign on [[Twitter]],<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/theoaisreal-oa-fans-launch-new-campaign-save-cult-netflix-show-2538104 |title=#TheOAisReal: The OA fans launch new campaign to save cult Netflix show |last=Reilly |first=Nick |date=2019-08-14 |website=NME |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> a [[Change.org]] petition,<ref name=\"people\" /> and by posting video of themselves performing The Movements from the show.<ref name=\"movements\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/the-oa-is-real-five-movements-videos/ |title=''The OA'' fans are doing the 'movements' to bring the show back to life |last=Schroeder |first=Audra |date=2019-08-13 |website=The Daily Dot |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> Additionally, the OA fan base raised funds for a digital billboard in Times Square.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/the-oa-billboard-save-netflix-season-3-1202168955/ |title=\u2018The OA\u2019 Fans Raise Over $5,000 for NYC Billboard Urging Netflix to Renew Canceled Series |last=Sharf |first=Zack |last2=Sharf |first2=Zack |date=2019-08-27 |website=IndieWire |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Marling wrote that she was moved by the fan support. One fan went on a hunger strike to protest for the show's return; Marling and Batmanglij visited her and offered her food and water.<ref name=\"vanity\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/08/the-oa-cancellation-brit-marling |title=\u2018The OA\u2019: Brit Marling Confirms It\u2019s Over, Despite Hopeful Conspiracy Theories |last=Nast |first=Cond\u00e9 |website=Vanity Fair |access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> Some fans online have put forward a theory that the cancellation announcement was just a meta [[publicity stunt]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McClusky |first1=Megan |title=''The OA'' Fans Have a Pretty Convincing Theory About the Show Not Really Being Cancelled |url=https://time.com/5651145/the-oa-cancelled-theories/ |accessdate=August 15, 2019 |work=Time |date=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vulture\">{{Cite web |title=Is ''The OA'' Fake-Canceled or Am I Just Losing My Mind? |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/the-oa-cancellation-reddit-fan-theories.html |last=Handler |first=Rachel |date=2019-08-13 |website=Vulture.com |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n\n==== Season one ====\nThe first season of ''The OA'' garnered a polarized but generally positive response from critics. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] assigned the first season a 77% critical approval rating and an average rating of 7.59/10 based on 66 reviews, writing that \"''The OA'' is more than OK.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_oa/s01 |title=The OA: Season 1 (2016) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], based on 17 reviews, assigned the series a rating of 61 out of 100, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-oa |title=The OA: Season 1 |publisher=[[CBS]] |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Most reviewers acknowledged the series' ambition and praised its mystery and direction. Reviewers made both favorable<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/netflix-the-oa-review-brit-marling-stranger-things |title=Netflix's New Sci-Fi Drama Isn't the Next ''Stranger Things''\u2014It's Better |first=Hillary |last=Busis |work=vanityfair.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/news/netflixs-spiritual-thriller-the-oa-will-surprise-many-14818752730014978/ |title=Netflix's spiritual thriller The OA will surprise many. |last=TV.com |work=tv.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/tv/the-oa-netflix-review-134804783.html |title=''The OA'': Your New Holiday Binge? |work=yahoo.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> and unfavorable<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4604523/the-oa-review-netflix/ |title=Review: Netflix's The OA Fails to Take Sci-Fi to New Heights |first=Daniel |last=D'Addario |work=time.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uproxx.com/sepinwall/the-oa-netflix-review/3/ |title=Netflix's ''The OA'' A Sci-Fi Mystery Not Worth Investigating |date=December 16, 2016 |work=uproxx.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/12/16/the-oa-review-netflix-s-top-secret-new-show-is-weird-as-hell.html |title=''The OA'' Review: Netflix's Top-Secret New Show Is Weird as Hell |first=Melissa |last=Leon |date=December 16, 2016 |work=thedailybeast.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> comparisons to another Netflix Original, ''Stranger Things.''\n\nJohn Doyle of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' wrote, \"''The OA'' is Netflix's strongest and strangest original production since ''Stranger Things''. In terms of substantive, original drama, it transcends it. Mind you, it is unclassifiable in the context of drama, mystery, science-fiction and fantasy, since it is straddling all sorts of lines and blurring them. It is outright astounding and brilliant, too.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> Tim Surette at ''[[TV Guide]]'' said that \"the final moments of Episode 5 \u2013 probably the best episode of the first season \u2013 was some of the most reaffirming television I've ever seen, not just for the show but for life itself. I've never really had this kind of a relationship with a series while watching it, but it's that experience that makes it well worth viewing.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-oa-review-netflix/ |title=Netflix's Mysterious The OA Is as Addictive as Stranger Things |date=December 16, 2016 |work=tvguide.com |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref> ''[[New York Magazine]]''{{'}}s review was entitled \"Netflix's ''The OA'' Is an Extraordinary, Binge-Worthy December Surprise\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/netflix-oa-is-your-binge-worthy-december-surprise.html |title=Netflix's The OA Is an Extraordinary, Binge-Worthy December Surprise |date=December 16, 2016 |work=vulture.com |access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTristram Fane Saunders of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave a mixed review of 3 out of 5 stars and noted the series' potential but criticized its similarity to fellow Netflix Original ''[[Stranger Things]]'', claiming that the series was attempting to be \"stranger than ''Stranger Things''{{-\"}} but \"on the basis of the first four episodes, the answer is a resounding no\". Saunders's review also highlighted the series' lack of originality and characterization, and derided the dialogue as \"portentous [and] self-consciously literary\". It also criticized the slow pace as \"glacial\". However, Saunders also acknowledged the series told an interesting and compelling story, writing that \"''The OA'' may be utter hokum, but you'll still be hooked.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/oa-netflix-spoiler-free-review-stranger-stranger-things/ |title=The OA, Netflix, spoiler-free review: 'stranger than ''Stranger Things''{{'}}|work=telegraph.co.uk |access-date=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Daniel Fienberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave a negative review, stating that the series was \"a failed, but not wholly worthless, experiment in TV auteurism\". Fienberg added \"the problem, of course, is that telling you what ''The OA'' is vaguely like is just another tease and telling you what it actually is<!--not a mistake--> is a recipe for disappointment, because after an enticing and somewhat infuriating build-up, ''The OA'' becomes something quite ludicrous as it stumbles toward a climax that is, if I'm generous, merely unearned and if I'm not being generous, a series of offensive overreaches.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/oa-review-956799 |title=''The OA'': TV Review |work=hollywoodreporter.com |access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' published diverging opinions about the series: its TV critic at the time, Sonia Saraiya, gave the show a mixed-to-negative review that praised the direction and acting but opined that overall \"it is hard to take ''The OA'' seriously\", detailing that \"none of it makes any sense\", and concluded that \"[a]s an exercise in vision, ''The OA'' is exciting. As that other thing \u2014 a television show \u2014 it\u2019s an especially cryptic attempt to say very little of consequence.\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/reviews/tv-review-netflix-the-oa-brit-marling-1201941411/ |title=TV Review: Netflix's ''The OA'' |first=Sonia |last=Saraiya |date=December 16, 2016 |work=variety.com |access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref> A few days later, on the other hand, the magazine's chief film critic Peter Debruge wrote an extremely positive column with the headline \"Why ''The OA'' is One of the Year's Most Important Films\", stating that the show's first season had \"the most effective ending [he had] ever seen in a TV series\", and that its \"final twist [...] left [him] crying uncontrollably for nearly half an hour\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/columns/the-oa-netflix-brit-marling-film-critic-appreciation-1201948242/ |title=Why The OA is One of the Year's Most Important Films |first=Peter |last=Debruge |date=December 24, 2016 |work=variety.com |access-date=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Season two ====\nThe second season received very positive reviews upon its release. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the second season has an approval rating of 92% based on 36 reviews, with an average rating of 7.7/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''The OA''{{'s}} second season provides satisfying answers to its predecessors' most maddening enigmas, all while maintaining the singular ambience that fans have come to crave.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The OA: Season 2 (2019) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_oa/s02 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 70 out of 100, based on 6 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-oa/season-2 |title=The OA: Season 2 |publisher=[[CBS]] |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 23, 2019}}</ref> Critics acknowledged the second season's vast improvements on its narrative and characterization, particularly praising its surrealism, directing and acting.\n\n[[Empire Magazine]] crowned The OA the best TV show of 2019 (so far) in September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Best TV Shows Of 2019 (So Far) |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-tv-2019/ |website=www.empireonline.com |url-status=live |access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> The Playlist stated in their review that: \"The OA: Part II packs each frame so dense with detail, that not one second of the new season's more-than-eight-hour runtime seems wasted, expositional, cheap, or unearned.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theplaylist.net/oa-part-ii-review-20190315/ |title=The OA Part II: The Ambitious Series Returns With A Superior Second Season That Gives Plenty Of Answers & Even More Questions |last=Arabian |first=Alex |date=2019-03-15 |website=The Playlist|}}</ref> Jesse Scheden of ''[[IGN]]'' gave ''The OA: Part II'' a score of 8.8 out of 10, saying the season is \"bigger, more ambitious and much weirder than its predecessor\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/23/netflixs-the-oa-season-2-review |title=Netflix's The OA Season 2 Review |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |date=2019-03-22 |website=IGN |access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> Rachel Syme of ''[[The New Republic]]'' praised the season, labeling the show as \"the best, most inaccessible show on television\", saying that \"[she wishes] more television was this unafraid to leave its audiences fumbling for understanding.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153410/best-inaccessible-show-television |title=The Best, Most Inaccessible Show on Television |last=Syme |first=Rachel |date=2019-03-28 |work=The New Republic |access-date=2019-04-02 |issn=0028-6583}}</ref> \n\nDaniel Fienberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote: \"The only thing I'm sure of when it comes to ''The OA'' is that the process of watching and experiencing an episode is unlike the viewing of any other show on TV and, good or bad, there's value in that.\" Alex McLevy of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' echoed that sentiment, saying \"sacrificing your expectations of plausibility feels like a worthwhile price of admission.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-oa-is-back-for-season-2-and-it-s-even-weirder-than-1833436588 |title=The OA is back for season 2, and it\u2019s even weirder than you remember |website=TV Club |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Jen Chaney of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]'' called the season a mind-bender and praised the way it depicted the aftermath of a school shooting.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/03/the-oa-part-ii-netflix-review.html |title=The OA Part II Is a Glorious, Ridiculous Mind-bender |website=www.vulture.com |url-status=live |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\nEd Power of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', gave it 4 out of 5 stars, and wrote that the show \"truly comes into its own when you stop attempting to piece together the storyline and instead submit to Marling and Batmanglij's vision.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/oa-season-2-review-netflixs-weirdinter-dimensional-soap-opera/ |title=The OA, season 2 review: Netflix's weird inter-dimensional soap opera is now even weirder |last=Power |first=Ed |date=2019-03-22 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=2019-10-13 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Emily Todd VanDerWerff of ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', initially critical of the first season, wrote of the series: \"over time, I kept thinking about it. And thinking about it. And thinking about it. Until I convinced myself that ''The OA'' is kind of genius, while simultaneously being incredibly silly.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/3/30/18284709/best-tv-march-the-oa-shrill-what-we-do-in-the-shadows-abbys-the-act |title=The 5 best TV debuts of March 2019 |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily Todd |date=2019-03-30 |website=Vox |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Haleigh Foutch of Collider said, \"Netflix has carved out a space for itself as a home for innovative genre storytelling, and ''The OA'' might just be their crowning achievement in that regard.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-oa-season-2-review/ |title=''The OA'' Season 2 Review: An Ambitious, Wondrous Exercise in WTF Storytelling |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |date=2019-03-22 |website=Collider |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| [[GLAAD Media Awards]]\n| [[GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]]\n| ''The OA''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/moonlight-netflix-supergirl-glaad-nominationss-nominations-1201974187/ |title=''Moonlight'', Netflix's ''The OA'', ''Supergirl'' Snag GLAAD Media Awards Nominations |work=Variety Reporter |first=Oriana |last=Schwindt |date=January 31, 2017 |accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama|Episodic Drama]]\n| Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb title}}\n\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OA, The}}\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American mystery television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related web series]]\n[[Category:Television shows about death]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Mystery drama web series]]\n[[Category:Near-death experiences in fiction]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Nonlinear narrative television series]]\n[[Category:Russian-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Science fantasy web series]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Surrealist television series]]\n[[Category:Teen drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Television series about missing people]]\n[[Category:Television series about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Television series by Anonymous Content]]\n[[Category:Television shows about disability]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Transgender-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Works about existentialism]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the television series|the peninsula in Scotland|The Oa|other uses of the letters OA|OA (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American mystery drama web television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The OA\n| image                    = The_OA.png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mystery film|Mystery]]\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n* [[Science fiction]]\n* [[Supernatural fiction|Supernatural]]\n* [[Fantasy (genre)|Fantasy]]\n}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brit Marling]]\n* [[Zal Batmanglij]]}}\n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brit Marling]]\n* [[Emory Cohen]]\n* [[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]]\n* [[Phyllis Smith]] \n* [[Alice Krige]]\n* [[Patrick Gibson (actor)|Patrick Gibson]]\n* [[Brendan Meyer]]\n* [[Brandon Perea]]\n* [[Ian Alexander (actor)|Ian Alexander]]\n* [[Jason Isaacs]]\n* [[Sharon Van Etten]]\n* [[Paz Vega]]\n* [[Will Brill]]\n* [[Chloe Levine]]\n* [[Kingsley Ben-Adir]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Rostam Batmanglij]]\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Rostam Batmanglij\n* Danny Bensi\n* Saunder Jurriaans\n* Jay Wadley\n* John Rossiter\n* Aaron Olson\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 2\n| num_episodes             = 16\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Brit Marling\n* Zal Batmanglij\n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n* [[Dede Gardner]]\n* [[Jeremy Kleiner]]\n* Sarah Esberg\n* [[Michael Sugar]]\n* Alison Engel\n* Blair Fetter\n* Nina Wolarsky\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Jill Footlick\n* Ashley Zalta\n}}\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[New York City]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyslovesfilm.tumblr.com/post/141970211803/march-is-busy-with-new-york-produced-films-and |title=March Is Busy With New York-Produced Films and Premieres |work=tumblr.com |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Orange County, New York]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orangecountynyfilm.org/filmed-in-orange-county/ |title=Filmed in Orange County NY \u2013 Orange County Film Office \u2013 Orange County, NY \u2013 OCNY FILM Office |work=orangecountynyfilm.org |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thephoto-news.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20160310/NEWS01/160319993/Monroe--Woodbury-High-School-to-be-the-set-of-new-Netflix-series |title=Monroe- Woodbury High School to be the set of new Netflix series \u2013 Monroe Woodbury NY \u2013 Local News |work=thephoto-news.com |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Groton, Connecticut]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theday.com/article/20160510/NWS01/160519954 |first=Kristina |last=Dorsey |title=Netflix series wraps a two-day shoot in Groton |work=The Day |date=May 10, 2016 |accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lol Crawley]]\n* Steven Meizler\n* Magnus Nordenhof J\u00f8nck\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Jonathan Alberts\n* Geraud Brisson\n* Matthew Hannam\n* [[Lisa Lassek]]\n* [[Andrew Weisblum]]\n* Alex O'Flinn\n* Neil Meiklejohn\n* Luke Ciarrocchi\n* Blake Holland\n* Saela Davis\n}}\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 31\u201371 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Plan B Entertainment]]\n* [[Anonymous Content]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Netflix|Netflix Studios]]<ref>https://trademarks.justia.com/867/68/the-86768143.html</ref>\n| network                  = Netflix\n| picture_format           = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital Plus]] 5.1 with [[Descriptive Video Service]] track\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2019|3|22}}\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/theoa\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       =\n}}\n'''''The OA''''' is an American [[Mystery film|mystery]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[web television]] series with [[science fiction]], [[Supernatural fiction|supernatural]], and [[fantasy (genre)|fantasy]] elements.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/doyle-netflixs-mysterious-the-oa-is-mind-bending-astounding-drama/article33344922/ |title=John Doyle: Netflix's mysterious ''The OA'' is mind-bending drama |work=theglobeandmail.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/could-oa-new-stranger-things-know-far-netflixs-mysterious-new/ |title=Could ''The OA'' be the new ''Stranger Things''? All we know so far about Netflix's mysterious new show |work=telegraph.co.uk |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> ''The OA'' debuted on [[Netflix]] on December 16, 2016.<ref name=\"DL trailer\">{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/the-oa-trailer-premiere-date-netflix-brit-marling-1201868844/ |title=''The OA'' Trailer: Netflix Releases First Look & Sets Premiere Date For Drama |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 12, 2016 |accessdate=December 12, 2016 |first=Erik |last=Pedersen}}</ref><ref name=\"digital spy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/news/a633457/netflix-orders-new-original-series-the-oa-starring-brit-marling.html#~p65N7NAAIF4OQo |title=Netflix orders new original series ''The OA'' starring Brit Marling |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=March 5, 2015 |accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> Created and executive produced by [[Brit Marling]] and [[Zal Batmanglij]], the series is their third collaboration.<ref name=\"DL trailer\" /><ref name=\"digital spy\" /> The series consists of two seasons of eight episodes each, nearly all directed by Batmanglij, and is produced by [[Plan B Entertainment]] and [[Anonymous Content]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/netflix-the-oa-brit-marling-zal-batmanglij-plan-b-anonymous-content-1201386609/ |title=Netflix Greenlights ''The OA'' Reuniting Brit Marling And Zal Batmanglij |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 5, 2015 |accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> In the series, Marling stars as a young woman named Prairie Johnson who resurfaces after having been missing for seven years. Prairie now calls herself \"The OA\" and can see, despite having been blind before her disappearance.\n\nOn February 8, 2017, Netflix renewed the series for a second season, dubbed \"Part II\", that was released on March 22, 2019. Although the OA was planned by its creators to be a five-part story told in five seasons,<ref name=\"Netflix VP Confirms 5 Season Plan\">{{cite news |last1=Travers |first1=Ben |title='The OA\u2019 Season 2: Netflix VP Says \u2018Fans Will Be Very Happy\u2019 with New Episodes and Confirms Five-Season Plan |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/07/the-oa-season-2-netflix-fantastic-five-season-plan-1201989088/ |accessdate=August 15, 2019 |work=IndieWire |date=June 29, 2018}}</ref> on August 5, 2019, Netflix canceled the series after two seasons, leaving the show with a [[cliffhanger]] ending.<ref name=\"THRCanceled\">{{cite news |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |title=''The OA'' Canceled After Two Seasons at Netflix |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/oa-canceled-two-seasons-at-netflix-1229215 |accessdate=August 5, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> ''The OA'' received generally favorable critical reception, averaging 77% on Part I and 92% on Part II on Rotten Tomatoes. The series' directing, visuals and acting were often singled out, as was its social impact.<ref name=\"The OA may have been Canceled, but Few Shows Can Claim the Same Social Impact\">{{cite news |last1=Osenlund |first1=R. Kurt R. |title=\u2018The OA\u2019 May Have Been Canceled, but Few Shows Can Claim the Same Social Impact |url=https://observer.com/2019/08/the-oa-netflix-canceled-brit-marling-message-petition-movement/ |accessdate=August 15, 2019 |work=Observer |date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n===Part I===\nThe series centers around Prairie Johnson, an adopted young woman who resurfaces after having been missing for seven years. Upon her return, Prairie calls herself \"The OA\" (for \"Original Angel\"), exhibits scars on her back, and can see, despite having been blind when she disappeared. The OA refuses to tell the [[FBI]] and her adoptive parents where she has been and how her eyesight was restored, and instead quickly assembles a team of five locals (four high school students and a teacher) to whom she reveals that information, also explaining her life story. Finally, she asks for their help to save the other missing people whom she claims she can rescue by opening a portal to [[Parallel universes in fiction|another dimension]].<ref name=\"Gilbert2019\">{{cite news |last1=Gilbert |first1=Sophie |title=The Radical Sincerity of The OA |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/03/the-return-of-the-oa-tvs-strangest-most-sincere-show/585208/ |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Part II===\nThe second season follows the OA as she traverses to another dimension and ends up in [[San Francisco]] to continue her search for her former captor Hap and her fellow captives. Prairie crosses paths with [[Private investigator|private eye]] Karim Washington and assists in his investigation of the surreal disappearance of a missing girl that involves an abandoned house with a supernatural history and an online puzzle game. Meanwhile, in the original dimension, a series of unfortunate events propels the OA's five companions to embark on a road trip across America to assist the OA on her journey.\n\n==Cast==\nThe following actors appear in the series:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/brit-marling-netflix-the-oa-mystery-trailer-video/ |title=Brit Marling's Netflix Series ''The OA'' Promises Mystery in First Trailer (Video) |work=The Wrap |date=December 12, 2016 |accessdate=December 12, 2016 |first=Linda |last=Ge}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/the-oa-brandon-perea-will-brill-cast-netflix-drama-series-1201708672/ |title=''The OA'': Brandon Perea & Will Brill Join Netflix Drama Series |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 24, 2016 |accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Main ===\n* [[Brit Marling]] as Prairie Johnson / the OA / Nina Azarova / \"Brit\"\n* [[Emory Cohen]] as Homer Roberts<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/01/oa-emory-cohen-defends-the-movements.html |title=The OA's Emory Cohen Defends the Movements |date=January 13, 2017 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]] as Abel Johnson, Prairie's adoptive father (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Phyllis Smith]] as Betty \"BBA\" Broderick-Allen<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/the-oa-netflix-phyllis-smith.html |title=The OA's Phyllis Smith Talks Angels, Turtles, and Dance Moves |date=December 23, 2016 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Alice Krige]] as Nancy Johnson, Prairie's adoptive mother (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Patrick Gibson (actor)|Patrick Gibson]] as Steve Winchell / \"Patrick Gibson\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/oa-breakout-star-patrick-gibson-mysteries-new-netflix-hit-and-possible-season-536880 |title=Inside Netflix's new cult hit ''The OA'' with breakout star Patrick Gibson |work=newsweek.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Brendan Meyer]] as Jesse \n* [[Brandon Perea]] as Alfonso \"French\" Sosa\n* [[Ian Alexander (actor)|Ian Alexander]] as Buck/Michelle Vu<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/the-oa-netflix-ian-alexander-buck.html |title=The OA's Ian Alexander on His Big Acting Debut and Trans Representation |date=December 22, 2016 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jason Isaacs]] as Hunter Aloysius \"Hap\" Percy / Dr. Percy / \"Jason Isaacs\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/news/a51705/jason-isaacs-the-oa-interview/ |title=''The OA''{{'}}s Jason Isaacs Is Just as Bewildered by the Netflix Series as You Are|date=December 21, 2016|work=esquire.com|accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Kingsley Ben-Adir]] as Karim Washington (season 2)\n* [[Will Brill]] as Scott Brown (season 2, recurring season 1)\n* [[Sharon Van Etten]] as Rachel DeGrasso (season 2, recurring season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/01/sharon-van-etten-the-oa-twin-peaks.html |title=Sharon Van Etten on The OA, Twin Peaks, and Her 'Surreal' Acting Debut |date=January 10, 2017 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Paz Vega]] as Renata Duarte (season 2, recurring season 1)\n* [[Chloe Levine]] as Angie (season 2, recurring season 1)\n\n=== Guest ===\n* [[Hiam Abbass]] as [[Khatun]] (season 1)\n* [[Evgeniya Brik#Family|Zoey Todorovsky]] as Nina Azarova, a young Prairie Johnson\n* Marcus Choi as Mr. Vu\n* Robert Eli as Ellis Gilchrist, a high school principal (season 1)\n* [[Nikolai Nikolaeff]] as Roman Azarov, Nina's father \n* [[Sean Grandillo]] as Miles Brekov (season 1)\n* Zachary Gemino as Carlos Sosa, Alfonso's brother \n* [[Riz Ahmed]] as Elias Rahim, an FBI trauma counselor\n* [[Robert Morgan (actor)|Robert Morgan]] as Stan Markham, a sheriff (season 1)\n* [[Michael Cumpsty]] as Leon Citro (season 1)\n* [[Bria Vinaite]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/kidding-cast-bernard-white-bria-vinaite-the-oa-1202395573/ |title=''Kidding'' Casts Bernard White; Bria Vinaite Joins ''The OA'' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=May 22, 2018 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> as Darmi (season 2)\n* [[Zendaya]] as Fola Uzaki (season 2)\n* [[Zo\u00eb Chao]] as Mo (season 2)\n* [[Ir\u00e8ne Jacob]] as \u00c9lodie (season 2)\n* [[Eijiro Ozaki]] as [[Azrael]] / Old Night, a giant octopus (voice) (season 2)\n* [[Vincent Kartheiser]] as Pierre Ruskin (season 2)\n* [[Liz Carr]] as Marlow Rhodes (season 2)\n* [[Melora Walters]] as Melody, who accompanies OA to the clinic in the episode \"Angel of Death\"\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| allreleased = y\n| released    = y\n\n| color1     = #1D1023\n| link1      = #Part I (2016)\n| episodes1  = 8\n| start1     = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n\n| color2     = #16365C\n| link2      = #Part II (2019)\n| episodes2  = 8\n| start2     = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n}}\n\n===Part I (2016)===\n{{Episode table |background=#1D1023 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=28 |director=13 |writer=30 |airdate=19 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Chapter 1: Homecoming\n| DirectedBy      = [[Zal Batmanglij]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Brit Marling]] & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = After disappearing seven years ago, Prairie Johnson returns to her parents, Nancy and Abel. Prairie disappeared blind, but now she can see, and insists that her name is \"The OA\". She does not reveal how she regained her eyesight, nor where she has been for the past seven years, although she makes vague allusions to being held hostage with others. OA tells Steve, a neighborhood bully, that she will save him from being sent to [[Boot camp (correctional)|boot camp]] in Asheville, if he presents her with four other strong people. That night, OA meets Steve in an abandoned house with three other boys from his school, \"French\", Buck, and Jesse, along with their teacher, Betty Broderick-Allen (\"BBA\"). She tells them that she was born in [[Russia]] as Nina Azarova, the daughter of a powerful [[Russian oligarch|oligarch]]. One day, following a premonition she had, the mafia knocked the bus of the oligarchs' children into a river. Nina had a [[near-death experience]] (NDE), where a woman named Khatun gave her the choice of returning to life. Nina came back blind after Khatun told her she would take her sight to protect her from the horrible things lying ahead.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Chapter 2: New Colossus\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = [[Melanie Marnich]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Continuing her story, OA says that her father sent her to a [[boarding school]] for blind children in America to protect her. However, her father died, and she was sent to live with her aunt who ran an illegal adoption service. Nancy and Abel adopted her and named her Prairie. For the next several years, Prairie had dreams and premonitions, for which her parents [[Antipsychotic|medicated]] her. In them, her father waited for her by the [[Statue of Liberty]]. She ran away on her 21st birthday to see him, but he did not appear. Instead, she met a scientist named \"Hap\". She ends her story for the night, and the boys begin to investigate whether she is telling the truth. French considers not going again when he gets a scholarship and wishes to focus on that, but Buck convinces him to come. The next night, she tells them that Hap was studying people that had NDEs, like she did. Prairie agreed to let Hap study her and flew on his private plane to his house, where he trapped her in a glass cage in his basement, with the other test subjects he had tricked over the years.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Chapter 3: Champion\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Dominic Orlando\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = In the present, a journalist approaches Prairie's mother, asking if she can write a book about their story. In the flashback, Prairie gets to know Homer, Scott and Rachel, the other three captives. Prairie makes Hap a sandwich, and he takes her on as a cook. He regularly pumps gas to their cages as part of an experiment, but the four cannot figure what that is, as the gas makes them pass out. BBA defends Steve from being sent to Asheville, convincing his parents to put him in [[special education]] instead. Prairie makes soup for Hap, who experiences anaphylactic shock when he eats it. He asks her to get an [[EpiPen]] from the bathroom, but there she discovers the dead body of a girl \"August\". The captives try to send a letter for help, but lose it. Prairie asks Hap about August, but becomes angry and pushes him down the stairs, and flees. She makes it as far as a cliff, but gets hit in the head by a rifle butt.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Chapter 4: Away\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Ruby Rae Spiegel\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Prairie meets Khatun in NDE. She is offered the choice of reuniting with her father but she chooses to return to help the others. Khatun, who shows she has a bird wing, offers Prairie to swallow a bird which will show her a way of traveling unknown to humans. She tells Prairie that five of them must work together to avert a great evil and that Prairie is \"the original\". Hap returns Prairie to her cage and she tells the others that she can see, they are all [[angels]], and their way out is by figuring Hap's experiment. In the present, BBA learns her brother Theo left her $50,000 in his will. OA meets an FBI counselor, Elias, who suggests to her that she focus on healing herself. In her story, Prairie and Rachel decide to suck Hap's [[Hyoscine#Crime|scopolamine-like]] gas, so that Homer experiences the experiment awake. Hap is revealed to be drowning them in water and recording the soundscape of their NDEs. It takes Homer four years, but he experiences an NDE awake, in which he manages to swallow a sea anemone. Prairie contemplates the possibility that she has a truer self who answers to something sounding like \"Away\" or \"Oh-A\".\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Chapter 5: Paradise\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = OA (having abandoned the name Prairie) and Homer perform the two movements they got from their NDEs. Hap forces Homer to seduce an NDE survivor in [[Cuba]] named Renata, to kidnap her. Homer ends up sleeping with her, which destroys the morale of the team and hurts OA. With Renata now locked back at Hap's, it's Scott's turn for the experiment. Scott begs Hap to spare him as he is too sick to survive another NDE and reveals OA can see, and her ideas about angels and how to escape. Hap proceeds with the experiment and Scott dies. Hap takes his body back to his cage, telling OA it's her fault. OA and Homer do their movements for hours, while facing each other with Scott in the middle. Unexpectedly, Scott returns to life and tells them they were right; if at least five people perform the movements, a door to another dimension opens. He has been given the third of five. Hap runs downstairs in shock that Scott is alive. In present day, OA tells the others the reason she gathered them is to teach them the movements so that she may travel to another dimension and rescue the others.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Chapter 6: Forking Paths\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Melanie Marnich\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = In the following three years Renata gets the fourth movement, OA and Homer scar themselves with depictions of them, so that they don't forget them, and Hap is watching closely and learning their movements as well. Hap visits his former mentor, Leon, in a morgue, in which Leon also runs similar experiments. Leon tells Hap he is very close to proving the existence of [[afterlife]], but Hap tells him he actually believes there are multiple dimensions, and his subjects have the means to make traveling between them possible. He also thinks he knows where their NDEs take place, and he intends to go see it with his own eyes. Leon pulls a gun on Hap demanding he reveals his breakthroughs. They fight and Hap kills him. Hap leaves the hospital and informs the staff to call the police to rescue Leon's subjects. Later, he asks OA to leave with him, make money using the first two healing movements, and run experiments on their own, but she turns him down. He reveals to her he thinks her NDEs take her to the [[rings of Saturn]]. A sheriff pays Hap a visit and discovers the hostages. He aims his gun at Hap.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Chapter 7: Empire of Light\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = OA has a premonition of a big space with a metallic sound, but she cannot tell what it means. She discusses it with Elias, who suggest that her \"psychic\" capability might be the result of being able to notice even the smallest cues around her. He also tells her to just accept whatever happens. Steve is being sent to Asheville but BBA uses her inheritance check to bribe the drivers to let him go. OA has dinner with her parents, when Nancy gets upset that she knows nothing about what happened to her daughter. OA explains that she scarred herself with the notations of the movements that open another dimension and she knows all this because she is \"the Original Angel\", which causes Nancy to slap her. French suggests to OA that she forgive Nancy and Abel and consider them as her parents because they are one of the reasons she came back from her NDEs. Steve accuses OA of using him and the rest of the group just so she can return to Homer, then stabs her leg with a pencil. She embraces him and calms him down. He asks her how she survived all those years and she replies she did because she was not alone.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Chapter 8: Invisible Self\n| DirectedBy      = Zal Batmanglij\n| WrittenBy       = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|12|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Hap convinces the sheriff that OA and Homer can cure his dying wife. Once healed, the sheriff's wife reveals she is an NDE survivor and can give them the fifth movement. Upon doing so, Hap kills her and her husband. He releases OA on the side of the road, telling her he will jump dimensions with the others. French breaks into OA's house, discovers some books that relate to OA's story (e.g., [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]''), and shares the revelation with the others. Days later, a [[School shooting|shooter]] approaches the school cafeteria where the boys are eating lunch. The boys and BBA, fearing for the lives of all present, desperately decide to enact OA's five movements. Bewildered, the shooter is easily subdued, but a stray bullet hits OA through the cafeteria window where she had been watching from outside. As medics tend to her, OA tells the boys and BBA that she can now feel herself going to another dimension.\n| LineColor       = 1D1023\n}}\n}}\n\n===Part II (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#16365C |overall=5 |season=5 |title=28 |director=13 |writer=30 |airdate=19 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = Chapter 1: Angel of Death\n |DirectedBy = [[Zal Batmanglij]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Brit Marling]] & Zal Batmanglij\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = In San Francisco, private detective Karim Washington agrees to help an elderly Vietnamese woman find her missing granddaughter, Michelle. Karim discovers Michelle's former hideout in an abandoned house, where she won tens of thousands of dollars playing \"Q Symphony,\" an online puzzle game. Karim theorizes the game is a recruitment and [[crowdsourcing]] tool created by tech guru Pierre Ruskin. Karim infiltrates the Q Symphony headquarters and finds inmates having their dreams monitored. Meanwhile, an adult Nina Azarova collapses in San Francisco as Prairie is shot; Prairie awakens in Nina's body, in an alternate dimension where Joe Biden is [[President of the United States|President]] in 2016. Nina was never blind, her father lived into old age, and Pierre Ruskin is her boyfriend. She contacts Nancy, who doesn't know her, having gone through with her original intention to adopt a boy. Due to her erratic behavior, Prairie is put on [[involuntary commitment|psychiatric hold]], but accepts an offer to check into the secluded Treasure Island psychiatric hospital. Homer is a [[residency (medicine)|resident]] psychiatrist and does not recognize her. Rachel, Scott, and Renata are patients. The facility's director is Hap, who greets her as \"Prairie.\"\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Chapter 2: Treasure Island\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Damien Ober & Nicki Paluga\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Hap continues to tighten his grip on Prairie by placing her in isolation from the other captives. Prairie unsuccessfully tries to help Homer remember his life from the original dimension. Out of sympathy, Homer decides to allow Prairie to reconcile with Scott, Rachel, and Renata. Rachel, having no longer the ability to speak, then uses objects to tell Prairie that Hap is planning to make a map across the multiple dimensions for his benefits. Meanwhile, Karim meets Marlow Rhodes, a former doctor who worked for Ruskin, who says that the house is a benefactor of the dreams. Karim realizes that the house is put on a Russian trust owned by Nina, Ruskin's girlfriend, and he decides to go see Prairie/Nina at the clinic. Hap takes Rachel to assist in his experiment on the clinic. Rachel comes across a classified area in Hap's experiment where she sees something horrific. Rachel stabs Hap in the stomach and Hap breaks her neck, killing her. Rachel's subconscious then transfers from her body to the original dimension from the prior season, where she finds sanctuary in the vanity mirror of Buck's room.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = Chapter 3: Magic Mirror\n |DirectedBy = [[Andrew Haigh]]\n |WrittenBy = Nicki Paluga & Dominic Orlando\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Back in the original dimension, Prairie died after being shot at the school. Her companions struggle to cope with the loss: Buck and BBA are about to move away; Steve and his new girlfriend Angie debate about teaching the movements to others to continue Prairie's legacy; Jesse becomes depressed following his brush with death; French struggles with his faith to OA. Suddenly, Buck sees a vision of Rachel on his vanity mirror and contacts the group, but the vanity was sold behind their back to a faraway department center, forcing them to drive hundreds of miles to successfully get the mirror. They take sanctuary at a church, and French temporarily splits from the group and has a one-night-stand with a man who recommends a psychic in Nebraska for support. The group then treks there, but the vanity accidentally gets broken. At the psychic's house, she helps Rachel come into contact with the group through a television. The group deduces from Rachel's messages that Prairie successfully made it to another dimension, and that it is \"only safe for BBA to go\" there.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Chapter 4: SYZYGY\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = After Rachel's murder, Hap incinerates her corpse. Karim visits Prairie/Nina to find out about her involvement in CURI. Prairie pleads with Karim to help her get out of the clinic in exchange for her assisting Karim in his case. They come to an agreement and they break out of the clinic. Homer goes on an unsuccessful date and Hap meets an enigmatic woman named Elodie who claims that she too is an inter-dimensional traveler like Hap. Meanwhile, Prairie and Karim head inside Nina's apartment and find a closet full of cassette tapes and a note marked \"SYZYGY\", in reference to a bar in downtown San Francisco. Prairie heads to the bar as Nina, alongside Karim, who looks for more clues in the venue. Prairie is strapped to a chair on the stage where a telepathic octopus, Old Night, straps his tentacles onto Prairie and has her communicate messages via his telepathy. Old Night figures out Prairie's true self, the OA, and strangles her to death to help her find clues in her investigation. A shocked Karim cuts one of Old Night's tentacles off, killing him, and resuscitates Prairie. They flee down the bar's basement and go through a door similar to one shown in Q Symphony.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = Chapter 5: The Medium & the Engineer\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Damien Ober & [[Henry Bean]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Prairie and Karim go through a sewer that leads them to inside the house on Nob Hill. They then solve some of the house's puzzles together, until they somehow split from each other. Karim explores the labyrinthine sections of the house and finds an unconscious Fola. He breaks through one of the walls, and escorts Fola, managing to save her in the process. Prairie journeys deeper inside, where she comes across a flock of living, telepathic trees that tell her that Hap is planning to make a powerful discovery that would make her lose her faith. The trees warn Prairie to form a tribe and that Nina is the key to doing so. Meanwhile, Homer comes across incriminating files that implicate Hap's involvement in CURI as his recorded conversations with Ruskin recall the history of the house. He also uncovers Hap's lie about Rachel, as he finds out that Rachel wasn't sent to another clinic. Meanwhile, in Elodie's apartment, Hap tries to knock out Elodie to use for his experiments. However, she catches wind of his intentions and uses cubes of dancing robots that initiate the movements, sending her to another dimension and killing her. A shocked Hap leaves the premises.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Chapter 6: Mirror Mirror\n |DirectedBy = Andrew Haigh\n |WrittenBy = Dominic Orlando & Claire Kiechel\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = BBA and the boys continue their journey across America. Their car breaks down and they hitchhike to a restaurant, where Jesse theorizes that they should head to Treasure Island in San Francisco to look for Prairie. They realize through television that they're wanted fugitives, and that an Amber alert is put out on Buck, a minor. They flee to avoid attention and take a bus trip to the house of BBA's dying uncle Carl in California where they stay for a day. However, things take a tragic turn when Jesse fatally overdoses on Carl's medication and the group tries to save him to no avail. They leave, but Steve stays behind to hopefully revive Jesse a second time. Unsuccessful and exhausted, he suddenly shaves his head. Meanwhile, Buck, Angie, French and BBA mourn Jesse's loss at a motel room and discuss going to Treasure Island, until Prairie's psychologist, Elias, arrives at their room and suggests that they should continue on with their journey as he claims that Prairie is going to need their help on her journey as the OA. The group then decides to trek to Treasure Island.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = Chapter 7: Nina Azarova\n |DirectedBy = [[Anna Rose Holmer]]\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Henry Bean\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Homer briefly confronts Hap about Rachel's whereabouts but Hap lies, telling Homer that Rachel killed herself. Homer then tells Hap that Scott explained about his NDE, where he sees Hap and Prairie together in a vision of a different dimension. Hap then contacts Scott, offering him his and Renata's freedom if he helps navigate the house on Nob Hill; Scott accepts the offer. Scott goes inside the house, but he suddenly collapses and is collected by Hap to be experimented on. Meanwhile, Prairie and Karim reunite as they find video footage of Michelle in the house's attic. They then have a falling out after Karim is unfazed by Prairie's claims about the dimensions and of Buck/Michelle. Prairie then crosses paths with Elodie, who advises her to let Nina have control of her body as well. Prairie drowns herself in a bathtub and resurrects as Nina. She then heads to Treasure Island and asks to talk to Hap. Meanwhile, Karim confronts Ruskin, who brags about getting away with his wrongdoings with the house because he believes nobody will come after him. He reveals that Michelle is alive but in a coma and that the house started to dream about Karim, calling for him to come back.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Chapter 8: Overview\n |DirectedBy = Zal Batmanglij\n |WrittenBy = Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|3|22}}\n |ShortSummary = Prairie helps Homer remember his memories and manages to convince Hap to show his research: mutated humans in a vegetated pool that serve as glimpses to other dimensions. They are revealed to be Scott and alternate versions of French, Jesse, and Steve. Prairie reverts back to herself and belittles Hap for his cruelty. Hap corners her into a spot surrounded by robots that initiate the movements to send them to another dimension. Hap fatally shoots Homer and Prairie tells a dying Homer to look for her in the next dimension. In the original dimension, Steve and the group reunite at Treasure Island, where BBA can sense OA's presence in danger and they initiate the movements to help her until Steve collapses. Karim makes it into the attic of the Nob Hill house, having solved the puzzle, and witnesses Prairie floating in the sky. She suddenly falls down, transitioning her to the third dimension with Hap. It is revealed that the next dimension is inside the soundstage of a television show, where an injured Prairie is referred to as \"Brit\" and Hap is her husband, \"Jason Isaacs\", who has a British accent. Karim notices a version of Buck in that universe and calls for him, as Buck is pulled inside the attic by Karim, waking up Michelle from her coma. Prairie and Hap get inside an ambulance but Steve, having successfully jumped dimensions, catches up, reuniting with Prairie and recognizing \"Jason Isaacs\" as Hap.\n |LineColor = 16365C\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe series was conceived by Brit Marling and Zal Batmanglij and they began working on the concept in December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theplaylist.net/director-zal-batmanglij-talks-creating-oa-season-2-will-evolve-much-interview-20170113/ |title=Director Zal Batmanglij Talks Creating ''The OA'', How Season 2 Will Evolve, And Much More [Interview] |date=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvmag.lefigaro.fr/programme-tv/the-oa-la-serie-revolutionnaire-de-netflix-racontee-par-sa-creatrice_a3e4d57c-c784-11e6-adad-3999a46f423c/ |title=The OA, la s\u00e9rie \"r\u00e9volutionnaire\" de Netflix racont\u00e9e par.. |last=lefigaro.fr |date=December 21, 2016 |work=lefigaro.fr |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> They spent two years working on ''The OA'' on their own,<ref name=\"Plan B\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marieclaire.com/culture/interviews/a24243/brit-marling-the-oa-interview/ |title=Brit Marling Spills on Her Mysterious New Netflix Show ''The OA'' |date=December 16, 2016 |work=marieclaire.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> before pitching to studios.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-oa-co-creator-on-stranger-things-comparisons-keeping-the-show-under-wraps/ |title=''The OA'' Co-Creator on ''Stranger Things'' Comparisons |date=December 16, 2016 |work=thewrap.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> From the early stages of development onward, they were telling the story out loud and noting one another's reactions to the story to refine it accordingly.<ref name=\"pitch\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/brit-marling-the-oa-netflix.html |title=Brit Marling on The OA, Netflix's Surprise Show About Dying |date=December 19, 2016 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> They found it difficult to summarize the series in a written story, so they developed it aurally. When executives read the script of the first hour, they asked if the story \"really [went] somewhere\". Marling and Batmanglij then began to tell the story from beginning to end,<ref name=\"pitch\" /> playing all the characters and acting out the big moments through many hours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/the-frame/2016/12/16/53836/how-the-creators-of-the-oa-made-a-long-format-mind/ |title=How the creators of ''The OA'' made a 'long format mind-bender' |first=Southern California Public |last=Radio |date=December 16, 2016 |work=scpr.org |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> They worked with [[Brad Pitt]]'s [[Plan B Entertainment]], which connected with the story and shared notes before it went to networks and studios.<ref name=\"Plan B\" /> Following a multiple-network bidding war, the series was first announced on March 5, 2015, when Netflix ordered eight one-hour long episodes with Plan B and [[Anonymous Content]] also on board. The announcement revealed that Marling would star, Batmanglij would direct, and both would write and executive produce. Marling and Batmanglij held similar positions in their previous two collaborations, ''[[Sound of My Voice]]'' and ''[[The East (film)|The East]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/brit-marling-zal-batmanglij-drama-779380 |title=Brit Marling-Zal Batmanglij Drama Gets Netflix Series Order (Exclusive) |work=hollywoodreporter.com |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Rostam Batmanglij]], Zal's brother, worked as one of the composers on the series, and he also wrote its theme music.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/16/t-magazine/entertainment/the-oa-brit-marling-netflix.html |title=Character Building: Brit Marling |date=December 16, 2016 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> He previously composed for both ''Sound of My Voice'' and ''The East''. Choreographer [[Ryan Heffington]] created The Movements, which are inspired by [[interpretive dance]]. Heffington first professionally worked with them on ''The East'', and had been an acquaintance of both from earlier than that.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/the-oa-movements-ryan-heffington-choreography.html |title=''The OA''{{'}}s Choreographer on the Meaning of the 'Movements'|date=December 21, 2016|work=vulture.com|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe final chapter of Part I includes a dedication to Allison Wilke. Wilke, also known professionally as A.W. Gryphon, was a producer on the series who died of breast cancer three days after the series was finished and a month before its release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/what-oa-who-allison-wilke-9597164 |title=Answers to your The OA questions including season 2 and who is Allison Wilke |first=Jo-Anne |last=Rowney |date=10 January 2017 |work=mirror.co.uk |accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Cancellation and fan response==\nOn August 5, 2019, Netflix canceled the series after two seasons,<ref name=\"THRCanceled\" /> leaving the show with a [[cliffhanger]] ending. Marling wrote that she and Batmanglij were \"deeply sad\" that they would not be able to finish the show.<ref name=\"people\">{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/tv/the-oa-canceled-after-2-seasons/ |title=Celebrities and Fans 'Devastated' After Netflix Cancels The OA |last=Claudia |first=Harmata |website=PEOPLE.com |access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> Fans responded with a #SaveTheOA<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/5/20755034/the-oa-canceled-netflix-season-2 |title=Netflix cancels The OA after two seasons |last=Haasch |first=Palmer |date=2019-08-05 |website=Polygon |access-date=2019-08-07}}\"Fans begin rallying behind #SaveTheOA\"</ref> and #TheOAisReal campaign on [[Twitter]],<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/theoaisreal-oa-fans-launch-new-campaign-save-cult-netflix-show-2538104 |title=#TheOAisReal: The OA fans launch new campaign to save cult Netflix show |last=Reilly |first=Nick |date=2019-08-14 |website=NME |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> a [[Change.org]] petition,<ref name=\"people\" /> and by posting video of themselves performing The Movements from the show.<ref name=\"movements\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/the-oa-is-real-five-movements-videos/ |title=''The OA'' fans are doing the 'movements' to bring the show back to life |last=Schroeder |first=Audra |date=2019-08-13 |website=The Daily Dot |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> Additionally, the OA fan base raised funds for a digital billboard in Times Square.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/the-oa-billboard-save-netflix-season-3-1202168955/ |title=\u2018The OA\u2019 Fans Raise Over $5,000 for NYC Billboard Urging Netflix to Renew Canceled Series |last=Sharf |first=Zack |last2=Sharf |first2=Zack |date=2019-08-27 |website=IndieWire |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Marling wrote that she was moved by the fan support. One fan went on a hunger strike to protest for the show's return; Marling and Batmanglij visited her and offered her food and water.<ref name=\"vanity\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/08/the-oa-cancellation-brit-marling |title=\u2018The OA\u2019: Brit Marling Confirms It\u2019s Over, Despite Hopeful Conspiracy Theories |last=Nast |first=Cond\u00e9 |website=Vanity Fair |access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> Some fans online have put forward a theory that the cancellation announcement was just a meta [[publicity stunt]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McClusky |first1=Megan |title=''The OA'' Fans Have a Pretty Convincing Theory About the Show Not Really Being Cancelled |url=https://time.com/5651145/the-oa-cancelled-theories/ |accessdate=August 15, 2019 |work=Time |date=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vulture\">{{Cite web |title=Is ''The OA'' Fake-Canceled or Am I Just Losing My Mind? |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/the-oa-cancellation-reddit-fan-theories.html |last=Handler |first=Rachel |date=2019-08-13 |website=Vulture.com |access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n\n==== Season one ====\nThe first season of ''The OA'' garnered a polarized but generally positive response from critics. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] assigned the first season a 77% critical approval rating and an average rating of 7.59/10 based on 66 reviews, writing that \"''The OA'' is more than OK.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_oa/s01 |title=The OA: Season 1 (2016) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], based on 17 reviews, assigned the series a rating of 61 out of 100, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-oa |title=The OA: Season 1 |publisher=[[CBS]] |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Most reviewers acknowledged the series' ambition and praised its mystery and direction. Reviewers made both favorable<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/netflix-the-oa-review-brit-marling-stranger-things |title=Netflix's New Sci-Fi Drama Isn't the Next ''Stranger Things''\u2014It's Better |first=Hillary |last=Busis |work=vanityfair.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/news/netflixs-spiritual-thriller-the-oa-will-surprise-many-14818752730014978/ |title=Netflix's spiritual thriller The OA will surprise many. |last=TV.com |work=tv.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/tv/the-oa-netflix-review-134804783.html |title=''The OA'': Your New Holiday Binge? |work=yahoo.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> and unfavorable<ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/4604523/the-oa-review-netflix/ |title=Review: Netflix's The OA Fails to Take Sci-Fi to New Heights |first=Daniel |last=D'Addario |work=time.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uproxx.com/sepinwall/the-oa-netflix-review/3/ |title=Netflix's ''The OA'' A Sci-Fi Mystery Not Worth Investigating |date=December 16, 2016 |work=uproxx.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/12/16/the-oa-review-netflix-s-top-secret-new-show-is-weird-as-hell.html |title=''The OA'' Review: Netflix's Top-Secret New Show Is Weird as Hell |first=Melissa |last=Leon |date=December 16, 2016 |work=thedailybeast.com |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> comparisons to another Netflix Original, ''Stranger Things.''\n\nJohn Doyle of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' wrote, \"''The OA'' is Netflix's strongest and strangest original production since ''Stranger Things''. In terms of substantive, original drama, it transcends it. Mind you, it is unclassifiable in the context of drama, mystery, science-fiction and fantasy, since it is straddling all sorts of lines and blurring them. It is outright astounding and brilliant, too.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\" /> Tim Surette at ''[[TV Guide]]'' said that \"the final moments of Episode 5 \u2013 probably the best episode of the first season \u2013 was some of the most reaffirming television I've ever seen, not just for the show but for life itself. I've never really had this kind of a relationship with a series while watching it, but it's that experience that makes it well worth viewing.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-oa-review-netflix/ |title=Netflix's Mysterious The OA Is as Addictive as Stranger Things |date=December 16, 2016 |work=tvguide.com |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref> ''[[New York Magazine]]''{{'}}s review was entitled \"Netflix's ''The OA'' Is an Extraordinary, Binge-Worthy December Surprise\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/12/netflix-oa-is-your-binge-worthy-december-surprise.html |title=Netflix's The OA Is an Extraordinary, Binge-Worthy December Surprise |date=December 16, 2016 |work=vulture.com |access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTristram Fane Saunders of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave a mixed review of 3 out of 5 stars and noted the series' potential but criticized its similarity to fellow Netflix Original ''[[Stranger Things]]'', claiming that the series was attempting to be \"stranger than ''Stranger Things''{{-\"}} but \"on the basis of the first four episodes, the answer is a resounding no\". Saunders's review also highlighted the series' lack of originality and characterization, and derided the dialogue as \"portentous [and] self-consciously literary\". It also criticized the slow pace as \"glacial\". However, Saunders also acknowledged the series told an interesting and compelling story, writing that \"''The OA'' may be utter hokum, but you'll still be hooked.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/oa-netflix-spoiler-free-review-stranger-stranger-things/ |title=The OA, Netflix, spoiler-free review: 'stranger than ''Stranger Things''{{'}}|work=telegraph.co.uk |access-date=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Daniel Fienberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave a negative review, stating that the series was \"a failed, but not wholly worthless, experiment in TV auteurism\". Fienberg added \"the problem, of course, is that telling you what ''The OA'' is vaguely like is just another tease and telling you what it actually is<!--not a mistake--> is a recipe for disappointment, because after an enticing and somewhat infuriating build-up, ''The OA'' becomes something quite ludicrous as it stumbles toward a climax that is, if I'm generous, merely unearned and if I'm not being generous, a series of offensive overreaches.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/oa-review-956799 |title=''The OA'': TV Review |work=hollywoodreporter.com |access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' published diverging opinions about the series: its TV critic at the time, Sonia Saraiya, gave the show a mixed-to-negative review that praised the direction and acting but opined that overall \"it is hard to take ''The OA'' seriously\", detailing that \"none of it makes any sense\", and concluded that \"[a]s an exercise in vision, ''The OA'' is exciting. As that other thing \u2014 a television show \u2014 it\u2019s an especially cryptic attempt to say very little of consequence.\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/reviews/tv-review-netflix-the-oa-brit-marling-1201941411/ |title=TV Review: Netflix's ''The OA'' |first=Sonia |last=Saraiya |date=December 16, 2016 |work=variety.com |access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref> A few days later, on the other hand, the magazine's chief film critic Peter Debruge wrote an extremely positive column with the headline \"Why ''The OA'' is One of the Year's Most Important Films\", stating that the show's first season had \"the most effective ending [he had] ever seen in a TV series\", and that its \"final twist [...] left [him] crying uncontrollably for nearly half an hour\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/columns/the-oa-netflix-brit-marling-film-critic-appreciation-1201948242/ |title=Why The OA is One of the Year's Most Important Films |first=Peter |last=Debruge |date=December 24, 2016 |work=variety.com |access-date=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Season two ====\nThe second season received very positive reviews upon its release. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the second season has an approval rating of 92% based on 36 reviews, with an average rating of 7.7/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''The OA''{{'s}} second season provides satisfying answers to its predecessors' most maddening enigmas, all while maintaining the singular ambience that fans have come to crave.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The OA: Season 2 (2019) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_oa/s02 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 70 out of 100, based on 6 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-oa/season-2 |title=The OA: Season 2 |publisher=[[CBS]] |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 23, 2019}}</ref> Critics acknowledged the second season's vast improvements on its narrative and characterization, particularly praising its surrealism, directing and acting.\n\n[[Empire Magazine]] crowned The OA the best TV show of 2019 (so far) in September of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Best TV Shows Of 2019 (So Far) |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-tv-2019/ |website=www.empireonline.com |url-status=live |access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> The Playlist stated in their review that: \"The OA: Part II packs each frame so dense with detail, that not one second of the new season's more-than-eight-hour runtime seems wasted, expositional, cheap, or unearned.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theplaylist.net/oa-part-ii-review-20190315/ |title=The OA Part II: The Ambitious Series Returns With A Superior Second Season That Gives Plenty Of Answers & Even More Questions |last=Arabian |first=Alex |date=2019-03-15 |website=The Playlist|}}</ref> Jesse Scheden of ''[[IGN]]'' gave ''The OA: Part II'' a score of 8.8 out of 10, saying the season is \"bigger, more ambitious and much weirder than its predecessor\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/23/netflixs-the-oa-season-2-review |title=Netflix's The OA Season 2 Review |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |date=2019-03-22 |website=IGN |access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> Rachel Syme of ''[[The New Republic]]'' praised the season, labeling the show as \"the best, most inaccessible show on television\", saying that \"[she wishes] more television was this unafraid to leave its audiences fumbling for understanding.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153410/best-inaccessible-show-television |title=The Best, Most Inaccessible Show on Television |last=Syme |first=Rachel |date=2019-03-28 |work=The New Republic |access-date=2019-04-02 |issn=0028-6583}}</ref> \n\nDaniel Fienberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote: \"The only thing I'm sure of when it comes to ''The OA'' is that the process of watching and experiencing an episode is unlike the viewing of any other show on TV and, good or bad, there's value in that.\" Alex McLevy of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' echoed that sentiment, saying \"sacrificing your expectations of plausibility feels like a worthwhile price of admission.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-oa-is-back-for-season-2-and-it-s-even-weirder-than-1833436588 |title=The OA is back for season 2, and it\u2019s even weirder than you remember |website=TV Club |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Jen Chaney of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]'' called the season a mind-bender and praised the way it depicted the aftermath of a school shooting.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/03/the-oa-part-ii-netflix-review.html |title=The OA Part II Is a Glorious, Ridiculous Mind-bender |website=www.vulture.com |url-status=live |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\nEd Power of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', gave it 4 out of 5 stars, and wrote that the show \"truly comes into its own when you stop attempting to piece together the storyline and instead submit to Marling and Batmanglij's vision.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/oa-season-2-review-netflixs-weirdinter-dimensional-soap-opera/ |title=The OA, season 2 review: Netflix's weird inter-dimensional soap opera is now even weirder |last=Power |first=Ed |date=2019-03-22 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=2019-10-13 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Emily Todd VanDerWerff of ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', initially critical of the first season, wrote of the series: \"over time, I kept thinking about it. And thinking about it. And thinking about it. Until I convinced myself that ''The OA'' is kind of genius, while simultaneously being incredibly silly.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/3/30/18284709/best-tv-march-the-oa-shrill-what-we-do-in-the-shadows-abbys-the-act |title=The 5 best TV debuts of March 2019 |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily Todd |date=2019-03-30 |website=Vox |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Haleigh Foutch of Collider said, \"Netflix has carved out a space for itself as a home for innovative genre storytelling, and ''The OA'' might just be their crowning achievement in that regard.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/the-oa-season-2-review/ |title=''The OA'' Season 2 Review: An Ambitious, Wondrous Exercise in WTF Storytelling |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |date=2019-03-22 |website=Collider |access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| [[GLAAD Media Awards]]\n| [[GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]]\n| ''The OA''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/moonlight-netflix-supergirl-glaad-nominationss-nominations-1201974187/ |title=''Moonlight'', Netflix's ''The OA'', ''Supergirl'' Snag GLAAD Media Awards Nominations |work=Variety Reporter |first=Oriana |last=Schwindt |date=January 31, 2017 |accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama|Episodic Drama]]\n| Brit Marling & Zal Batmanglij\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==E